    "introduction": "<strong>What is an Overloaded Sentence?</strong><br>An overloaded sentence contains too much information, making it confusing or difficult to read. While expanding sentences is good, adding too many clauses or phrases can create a tangled mess.<br><br>#### Signs of an Overloaded Sentence:<br>1. Too many conjunctions (and, so, but, because) in a row.<br>2. You lose track of the main subject and verb.<br>3. It takes too long to read aloud without taking a breath.<br><br>#### How to Fix Them:<br>- <strong>Break it down:</strong> Split the long sentence into two or three shorter, clearer sentences.<br>- <strong>Remove repetition:</strong> Take out unnecessary words or repetitive phrases.<br><br><strong>Overloaded:</strong> The dog ran into the street, and a car almost hit him, but he jumped out of the way, because he is very fast, so he was safe.<br><strong>Fixed:</strong> The dog ran into the street and was almost hit by a car. Luckily, he jumped out of the way because he is very fast."
