    "stepByStep": "You must memorize these pairings. There is no trick.<br><br>#### Present Tense<br>- <strong>I</strong> -> am<br>- <strong>He, She, It (Singular Noun)</strong> -> is<br>- <strong>You, We, They (Plural Noun)</strong> -> are<br><br><em>Examples:</em><br>- I <strong>am</strong> tired.<br>- The car (it) <strong>is</strong> fast.<br>- The students (they) <strong>are</strong> smart.<br><br>#### Past Tense<br>- <strong>I, He, She, It (Singular Noun)</strong> -> was<br>- <strong>You, We, They (Plural Noun)</strong> -> were<br><br><em>Examples:</em><br>- I <strong>was</strong> tired.<br>- The car <strong>was</strong> fast.<br>- The students <strong>were</strong> smart.",
    "indonesianLearnerWarning": "In Indonesian, \"adalah\" is used for everything, or omitted entirely (Dia marah = He angry). In English, you must remember to include the Be verb, AND you must choose the right one. Do not just use \"is\" for everything! (e.g., Don't say \"They is happy\")."
