    "introduction": "Learn how the verb agrees with the noun that follows 'there'.",
    "stepByStep": "In most English sentences, the subject comes first. (The dog is here).<br>But in \"There\" sentences, the order is flipped. The subject comes AFTER the verb.<br><br>Look <em>past</em> the verb to find the subject:<br>- There <strong>is</strong> <em>a car</em> in the driveway. (The true subject is \"a car\" - Singular -> is).<br>- There <strong>are</strong> <em>three cars</em> in the driveway. (The true subject is \"three cars\" - Plural -> are).<br>- There <strong>is</strong> <em>some water</em> on the floor. (The true subject is \"water\" - Uncountable -> is).",
    "indonesianLearnerWarning": "In Indonesian, the word \"Ada\" is used for everything, whether it is one thing, many things, past, or present. (Ada mobil, Ada lima mobil). In English, you must change the verb to match the quantity! You cannot just say \"There is\" for everything."
