    "introduction": "Find the real subject by ignoring extra phrases between the subject and verb.",
    "stepByStep": "<strong>The Trick:</strong> When you read a long sentence, mentally \"cross out\" all prepositional phrases (starting with <em>of, in, on, with, for, along with, as well as</em>). The word left over is your true subject!<br><br>#### Example 1: Prepositional Phrases<br>- <em>Sentence:</em> The <strong>box</strong> of chocolates (is/are) on the table.<br>- <em>Process:</em> Cross out the prepositional phrase (\"of chocolates\"). The word \"chocolates\" is NOT the subject. The subject is \"box\".<br>- <em>Correct:</em> The <strong>box</strong> of chocolates <strong>is</strong> on the table.<br><br>#### Example 2: Along with / As well as<br>These phrases look like \"and\", but they do not make the subject plural! Cross them out.<br>- <em>Sentence:</em> The <strong>teacher</strong>, along with the students, (is/are) going.<br>- <em>Process:</em> Cross out (\"along with the students\").<br>- <em>Correct:</em> The <strong>teacher</strong>, along with the students, <strong>is</strong> going.<br><br>#### Example 3: Relative Clauses<br>- <em>Sentence:</em> The <strong>car</strong> that hit the two trees (was/were) badly damaged.<br>- <em>Process:</em> Cross out the clause (\"that hit the two trees\").<br>- <em>Correct:</em> The <strong>car</strong> that hit the two trees <strong>was</strong> badly damaged.",
    "indonesianLearnerWarning": "In Indonesian, sentences are often constructed as \"Topik-Komentar\" (Topic-Comment). If a plural word is near the verb, it feels natural to use a plural verb. You must train your eyes to scan backwards to the very first noun in the sentence to find the true Subject in English!"
